#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:2
msgid "Historical Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:4
msgid ""
"This page lists features or behavior from previous versions of pytest which "
"have changed over the years. They are kept here as a historical note so "
"users looking at old code can find documentation related to them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:8
msgid "cache plugin integrated into the core"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:12
msgid ""
"The functionality of the :ref:`core cache <cache>` plugin was previously "
"distributed as a third party plugin named ``pytest-cache``.  The core plugin "
"is compatible regarding command line options and API usage except that you "
"can only store/receive data between test runs that is json-serializable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:19
msgid "funcargs and ``pytest_funcarg__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:23
msgid ""
"In versions prior to 2.3 there was no ``@pytest.fixture`` marker and you had "
"to use a magic ``pytest_funcarg__NAME`` prefix for the fixture factory.  "
"This remains and will remain supported but is not anymore advertised as the "
"primary means of declaring fixture functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:31
msgid "``@pytest.yield_fixture`` decorator"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:35
msgid ""
"Prior to version 2.10, in order to use a ``yield`` statement to execute "
"teardown code one had to mark a fixture using the ``yield_fixture`` marker. "
"From 2.10 onward, normal fixtures can use ``yield`` directly so the "
"``yield_fixture`` decorator is no longer needed and considered deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:42
msgid "``[pytest]`` header in ``setup.cfg``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:46
msgid ""
"Prior to 3.0, the supported section name was ``[pytest]``. Due to how this "
"may collide with some distutils commands, the recommended section name for "
"``setup.cfg`` files is now ``[tool:pytest]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:50
msgid ""
"Note that for ``pytest.ini`` and ``tox.ini`` files the section name is "
"``[pytest]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:55
msgid "Applying marks to ``@pytest.mark.parametrize`` parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:59
msgid ""
"Prior to version 3.1 the supported mechanism for marking values used the "
"syntax::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:62
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"test_input,expected\", [\n"
"    (\"3+5\", 8),\n"
"    (\"2+4\", 6),\n"
"    pytest.mark.xfail((\"6*9\", 42),),\n"
"])\n"
"def test_eval(test_input, expected):\n"
"    assert eval(test_input) == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"This was an initial hack to support the feature but soon was demonstrated to "
"be incomplete, broken for passing functions or applying multiple marks with "
"the same name but different parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:75
msgid "The old syntax is planned to be removed in pytest-4.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:79
msgid "``@pytest.mark.parametrize`` argument names as a tuple"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:83
msgid ""
"In versions prior to 2.4 one needed to specify the argument names as a "
"tuple.  This remains valid but the simpler ``\"name1,name2,...\"`` comma-"
"separated-string syntax is now advertised first because it's easier to write "
"and produces less line noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:90
msgid "setup: is now an \"autouse fixture\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:94
msgid ""
"During development prior to the pytest-2.3 release the name ``pytest.setup`` "
"was used but before the release it was renamed and moved to become part of "
"the general fixture mechanism, namely :ref:`autouse fixtures`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:103
msgid "Conditions as strings instead of booleans"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:107
msgid ""
"Prior to pytest-2.4 the only way to specify skipif/xfail conditions was to "
"use strings::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:110
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(\"sys.version_info >= (3,3)\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:115
msgid ""
"During test function setup the skipif condition is evaluated by calling "
"``eval('sys.version_info >= (3,0)', namespace)``.  The namespace contains "
"all the module globals, and ``os`` and ``sys`` as a minimum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:119
msgid ""
"Since pytest-2.4 :ref:`boolean conditions <condition booleans>` are "
"considered preferable because markers can then be freely imported between "
"test modules. With strings you need to import not only the marker but all "
"variables used by the marker, which violates encapsulation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:124
msgid ""
"The reason for specifying the condition as a string was that ``pytest`` can "
"report a summary of skip conditions based purely on the condition string. "
"With conditions as booleans you are required to specify a ``reason`` string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:128
msgid ""
"Note that string conditions will remain fully supported and you are free to "
"use them if you have no need for cross-importing markers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:131
msgid ""
"The evaluation of a condition string in ``pytest.mark."
"skipif(conditionstring)`` or ``pytest.mark.xfail(conditionstring)`` takes "
"place in a namespace dictionary which is constructed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:135
msgid ""
"the namespace is initialized by putting the ``sys`` and ``os`` modules and "
"the pytest ``config`` object into it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:138
msgid ""
"updated with the module globals of the test function for which the "
"expression is applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:141
msgid ""
"The pytest ``config`` object allows you to skip based on a test "
"configuration value which you might have added::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:144
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(\"not config.getvalue('db')\")\n"
"def test_function(...):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:148
msgid "The equivalent with \"boolean conditions\" is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:150
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(not pytest.config.getvalue(\"db\"),\n"
"                    reason=\"--db was not specified\")\n"
"def test_function(...):\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:157
msgid ""
"You cannot use ``pytest.config.getvalue()`` in code imported before pytest's "
"argument parsing takes place.  For example, ``conftest.py`` files are "
"imported before command line parsing and thus ``config.getvalue()`` will not "
"execute correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:163
msgid "``pytest.set_trace()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:167
msgid ""
"Previous to version 2.4 to set a break point in code one needed to use "
"``pytest.set_trace()``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:169
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ...\n"
"    pytest.set_trace()    # invoke PDB debugger and tracing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:175
msgid ""
"This is no longer needed and one can use the native ``import pdb;pdb."
"set_trace()`` call directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:177
msgid "For more details see :ref:`breakpoints`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:180
msgid "\"compat\" properties"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:184
msgid ""
"Access of ``Module``, ``Function``, ``Class``, ``Instance``, ``File`` and "
"``Item`` through ``Node`` instances have long been documented as deprecated, "
"but started to emit warnings from pytest ``3.9`` and onward."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/historical-notes.rst:187
msgid ""
"Users should just ``import pytest`` and access those objects using the "
"``pytest`` module."
msgstr ""
